The `folly/Poly.md` document does not mention `noexcept` at all. Consider this example

```
#include <folly/Poly.h>
#include <iostream>

struct IDrawable {
  template <typename Base> struct Interface : Base {
    void draw(std::ostream& out) const /* noexcept */ {
      folly::poly_call<0>(*this, out);
    }
  };

  template <typename T> using Members = folly::PolyMembers<&T::draw>;
};

struct Circle {
  void draw(std::ostream& out) const /* noexcept */ { out << "Cirlce.\n"; }
};

using Drawable = folly::Poly<IDrawable>;

int main() {
  Drawable obj = Circle{};
  obj.draw(std::cout);
}
```

Uncommenting any `noexcept` breaks on my machine (using clang from 2017-11-25 and folly from 2017-12-25)

I attached the error message for uncommenting `Circle::draw`'s  `noexcept` specifier.

[error.log](https://github.com/facebook/folly/files/1639659/error.log)

Would it make sense to create a construct StreamingPromise that can `setValue` multiple times? The use case is that when the call site is something like:

`
serviceProxy.getResponse().then([](const ResponsePart&  response)
{
    //  Do something with partial response
});

`

It would be great to have the `ServiceProxy::getResponse` return a `Future` that can be set multiple times by the `Promise` that was created the first time it was called.

Is this the limitation of the Future/Promise paradigm or would it be a good idea to support something like 'StreamingPromise' ?

